Kenya has recorded 41 new COVID-19 cases from
a sample size of 5,211 tested in the last 24 hours, marking a positivity rate
of 0.7 per cent. This brings the total number of cases
confirmed in the country to 322,822 out of the 3,351,782 tests conducted so
far. From the cases, 33 are Kenyans while 8 are
foreigners; 23 are males and 18 are females, while the youngest is a
one-year-old child and the oldest is 73 years. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi
leads with 28 cases followed by Mombasa 3, Tharaka Nithi 3, Homa Bay 1, Kilifi
1, Kwale 1, Mandera 1, Turkana 1, Uasin Gishu 1 and Vihiga 1. The Ministry of Health, in a statement on
Thursday, said 22 patients recovered from the disease; 19 were discharged from
various health facilities countrywide while 3 are from the Home-Based Isolation
and Care program. Total recoveries now stand at 303,166. However, no deaths were recorded within the
period, thus cumulative fatalities still stand at 5,638. The ministry also noted that 95 patients are
currently admitted in various health facilities countrywide, while 542 are
under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. “4 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit
(ICU) and all of them are on ventilatory support. Another 13 patients are on
supplemental oxygen and all of them are in the general wards. No patient is in
the High Dependency Unit (HDU),” said Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe. On the vaccination exercise, CS Kagwe
announced that 16,379,356 vaccines had been administered across the country as
of February 23, 2022. Of these, 7,730,560 are partially vaccinated
while those fully vaccinated are 7,463,909. “The total number of vaccines administered in
the last 24 hours is 55,453 while the total number of people fully vaccinated in
the last 24 hours is 31,960,” stated the CS. He added that 938,487 are doses administered
to those between 15 to 17 years while 246,400 are booster doses.  “The uptake of the second dose among those
who received their first dose was at 63.3%. The proportion of adults fully
vaccinated was 27.4%. The government is working towards vaccinating a targeted
population of 27,246,033,” added Kagwe.